Which of the following reactions is allowed? If forbidden, state the reason:
(a) \(\pi^- + \mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{K}^- + \Sigma^+\);
(b) \(\mathrm{d} + \mathrm{d} \rightarrow \mathrm{He}^4 + \pi^0\);
(c) \(\mathrm{K}^- + \mathrm{p} \rightarrow \mathrm{E}^- + \mathrm{K}^+\).

solution:
Using the charge neutrality equation:

\[
p + N_{D} + p_{A} = n + N_{A} + n_{D}
\]

where \(p = 0\) and \(p_{A} = 0\), the probability of electrons occupying the donor impurity energy level is:

\[
\begin{gathered}
f_{\mathrm{D}} = \frac{1}{1 + \frac{1}{2} \mathrm{e}^{\frac{E_{\mathrm{D}} - E_{\mathrm{F}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}}} \\
n_{\mathrm{D}} = N_{\mathrm{D}} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + \frac{1}{2} \mathrm{e}^{\frac{E_{\mathrm{D}} - E_{\mathrm{F}}}{k_{\mathrm{B}} T}}} = N_{\mathrm{D}} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + \frac{1}{2} \mathrm{e}^0} = \frac{2}{3} N_{\mathrm{D}}
\end{gathered}
\]

Substituting into the charge neutrality equation, we get \(N_{\mathrm{D}} = n + N_{A} + \frac{2}{3} N_{\mathrm{D}}\), which is:

\[
\frac{1}{3} N_{\mathrm{D}} = n + N_{A} = 5 \times 10^{15} + 1 \times 10^{15} = 6 \times 10^{15} \ \mathrm{cm}^{-3}
\]

Thus, the donor impurity concentration in the doped material is:

\[
N_{\mathrm{D}} = 1.8 \times 10^{16} \ \mathrm{cm}^{-3}
\]

The position of the Fermi energy level in the semiconductor silicon can be found using the electron concentration formula \(n=N_C e^{-\frac{E_C-E_F}{k_B T}}\), yielding

\[
\begin{aligned}
E_F & =E_C-k_B T \ln \frac{N_C}{N_D}=E_C-k_B T \ln \left(\frac{2.8 \times 10^{19}}{1 \times 10^{15}}\right)=E_C-0.026 \times 10.24 \\
& =E_C-0.27 \ \text{eV}
\end{aligned}
\]

For ionic crystals, if we neglect the damping effect (i.e., take the damping term as \(r = 0\)), \(\varepsilon(\omega)\) becomes a real number.

\[
\varepsilon(\omega) = \varepsilon(\infty) + \frac{[\varepsilon(0) - \varepsilon(\infty)] \omega_{\mathrm{T}}^{2}}{\omega_{\mathrm{T}}^{2} - \omega^{2}}
\]

From the given conditions, when \(\omega = \omega_{0} = \frac{2 \pi c}{\lambda_{0}} = 6.15 \times 10^{13} \, \mathrm{s}^{-1}\), the reflectance \(R = 0\), implying \(\varepsilon(\omega) = 1\), yielding

\[
\begin{gathered}
1 = \varepsilon(\infty) + \frac{[\varepsilon(0) - \varepsilon(\infty)] \omega_{\mathrm{T}}^{2}}{\omega_{\mathrm{T}}^{2} - \omega_{0}^{2}} \\
\omega_{\mathrm{T}} = \left[\frac{\varepsilon(\infty) - 1}{\varepsilon(0) - 1}\right]^{1 / 2} \omega_{0} = 0.505 \omega_{0} = 3.11 \times 10^{13} \, \mathrm{s}^{-1}
\end{gathered}
\]

According to the LST relation:

\[
\frac{\omega_{\mathrm{L}}^{2}}{\omega_{\mathrm{T}}^{2}} = \frac{\varepsilon(0)}{\varepsilon(\infty)}
\]

Therefore,

\[
\omega_{\mathrm{L}} = \left[\frac{\varepsilon(0)}{\varepsilon(\infty)}\right]^{1 / 2} \omega_{\mathrm{T}} = 0.817 \omega_{0} = 5.03 \times 10^{13} \, \mathrm{s}^{-1}
\]

Linearly polarized light can be decomposed into right-handed and left-handed circularly polarized light.

\[
\begin{aligned}
\boldsymbol{E} &= \boldsymbol{E}_+ + \boldsymbol{E}_- \\
& = \frac{E_0}{2} 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
\mathrm{i}
\end{bmatrix}
e^{\mathrm{i}(k_+ z - \omega t)} + \frac{E_0}{2} 
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-\mathrm{i}
\end{bmatrix}
e^{\mathrm{i}(k_- z - \omega t)} \\
& = E_0 
\begin{bmatrix}
\cos \frac{k_+ - k_-}{2} z \\
- \mathrm{i} \sin \frac{k_+ - k_-}{2} z
\end{bmatrix}
e^{\mathrm{i}\left(\frac{k_+ + k_-}{2} z - \omega t\right)}
\end{aligned}
\]

Looking in the direction of light propagation, the rotation angle of the polarization plane in the clockwise direction is

\[
\theta = \frac{k_+ - k_-}{2} z = \frac{\omega z}{2 c} (n_+ - n_-) = \frac{\omega z}{2 c} \Delta n
\]

Assuming \(\Delta n \ll n\), i.e., \(\frac{\varepsilon_0 \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 \omega B}{N e (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)} \ll 1\), then

\[
\begin{aligned}
n_\pm &= \sqrt{1 + \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2}{\omega_0^2 - \omega^2} \left(1 \pm \frac{\varepsilon_0 \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 \omega B}{N e (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)}\right)} \\
&\approx \sqrt{1 + \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2}{\omega_0^2 - \omega^2}} \pm \frac{1}{2} \frac{\varepsilon_0 \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^4 \omega B}{N e (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)^2 \sqrt{1 + \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2}{\omega_0^2 - \omega^2}}}
\end{aligned}
\]

The approximation made above satisfies the condition \(\Delta n \ll n\), thus

\[
\begin{aligned}
\Delta n &= \frac{\varepsilon_0 \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^4 \omega B}{N e (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2) \sqrt{(\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)^2 + \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)}} \\
&= \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 \omega_0 \omega B}{(\omega_0^2 - \omega^2) \sqrt{(\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)^2 + \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)}}
\end{aligned}
\]

In the equation, \(\omega_0 = \frac{e B}{m}\).  
Substituting \(\Delta n\) into the formula for the rotation angle gives

\[
\begin{aligned}
\theta &= \frac{\omega z}{2c} \Delta n \\
&= \frac{\omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 \omega^2 \omega_0}{2c (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2) \sqrt{(\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)^2 + \omega_{\mathrm{p}}^2 (\omega_0^2 - \omega^2)}} z
\end{aligned}
\]
